Project Management - Quality  (Oxford's Contractor)
Member in Supplier Workstream integration for Wright Medical (WM) acquisition:
•	Oversee the integration project for Wright Medical (WM) sites out of US
•	Ensure the deployment of the purchasing control process;
•	Unify and support WM stakeholders throughout the integration project; 
•	Manage supplier quality engineers (up to 5 people in transverse);
•	Oversee the execution of the audit program and the implementation of supplier quality and change control agreements;
•	Identify and mitigate gaps and integration risks;
•	Implement supplier improvement quality plans;
•	Provide reporting to Merge & Acquisition and Sustaining team members.
	Succès :
	Wright Medical stakeholders' adherence to the integration project.
	Reducing gaps and securing the integration project.

Manage the development of a product line for power electronic applications:
•	Define project framework (investments, resources, planning, specification…);
•	Conduct risk analyses and improvement actions;
•	Monitor and control the execution of the project;
•	Ensure the achievement of quality, cost and deadline objectives;
•	Lead the project teams (up to 8 people – direct & transversal); 
•	Provide project reporting to internal and external clients.

	Success (es):
	NPI of LEM’s first digital product range.
	NPI of LEM’s first miniature transducer.

Lead innovation partnership programs with external partners:
•	Lead working session with multidisciplinary teams;
•	Monitor and control the execution of external projects;
•	Lead the project teams (up to 4 people – direct & transversal); 
•	Present to the senior management and board members’ innovative projects aligned with LEM’s strategy;
•	IP due diligence of partners’ assets.

	Success (es):
	Development of the process “Innovation partnerships management”.
Development and deployment of a novel current sensing technology.

Management at the group level of the project quality, the supplier quality, the quality manufacturing, the laboratory, the customer return and HQSE departments:
•	Define and deploy the Quality strategy; 
•	Establish and monitor the budget;
•	Promote a philosophy of continuous improvement;
•	Lead worldwide the quality teams (up to 20 people – direct & transversal);
•	Plan and drive internal, customer and regulatory audits;
•	Guaranty the implementation of corrective and preventive actions 
•	Manage the performance indicators;
•	Provide timely reports to the CEO. 

	Success (es):
Corporate promotion of a zero-incident culture. 
Corporate deployment of an improved customer returns process.

Lead at group level the selection, qualification and sustainability of LEM’s suppliers (Asia, Europe, Maghreb):
•	Define the supplier quality management strategy;
•	Lead worldwide the quality teams (up to 5 people– direct & transversal);
•	Perform the system and manufacturing audit; 
•	Monitor the supplier performance indicators and implement relevant improvement plans;
•	Guaranty the implementation of corrective and preventive actions; 
•	Provide timely reports to the CEO. 

Success (es):
Development and deployment at the group level the process “Supplier Quality management”.
Consolidation at the group level of LEM supplier portfolio.

